title: For Sale/Trade:  Husqvarna m1887 Nagant Revolver with Reloading supplies
postcontent:
Up for sale is my Nagant revolver made by Husqvarna in Sweden. Selling to Cabelas this Friday if I don't get any takers here.

Production date is 1897, so it is considered an antique and as such can be shipped through regular mail and sold with no FFL involved. This is the very scarce cousin to the Russian Nagant revolver. Under 25,000 were produced and many were converted to .22lr in the 1960's by importers making the original caliber guns a rarity. This revolver was used by the Swedish Army until the 1930's when they were replaced and then reissued to the home guard during WWII. Most were imported to the US in the late 1960's.

It shoots the 7.5mm Swedish black powder cartridge which has not been produced in over 50 years. The round is identical in size and pressure to the smokeless 7.5mm Swiss Ordinance (not the rifle round) and this round can be found online at specialty retailers. However where this revolver shines, is that you can reload ammo for it at $0.05 a round, the cost of .22lr. Reloading data is identical to .32 S+W Long and the rounds are nearly identical in dimensions.

Many people shoot .32 S+W Long with CAST LEAD BULLETS ONLY (jacked bullets will get lodged in the barrel) without any troubles, but I have not tried this.

Included are 300 new production 7.5 Swiss Ordinance cases that can be reloaded up to 10-15 times each. Also included is the correct .314 caliber Lee bullet mould, unused. All you need are a set of 7.5 Swiss Ordinance dies (substitutions available) and a casting/loading setup to make your own ammo.

I have never fired this gun, but it is 100% functional. It is a standard double/single action revolver with a heavy double action pull and a very crisp single action.

Condition is pretty good for a gun that is 118 years old. Bluing is at 70% with some light pitting. Strawing is at 40%. Bore is bright with no pitting and strong rifling. 

Price of the revolver and loading supplies is $500 OBO which is a fair market value. These revolvers typically sell on Gunbroker in the $430 range. Feel free to make an offer, I'm looking to move this out soon. I have $100 in the cases and mould alone. I would consider trading for cases of ammo in .223, 9mm, .30-06, etc.

I have a CPL. Will meet in the parking lot of the Tulalip Cabelas. I-594 exempt as an antique, no FFL required.

I don't respond to gibberish, phone numbers, or lowball offers. All communication via email so everything is in writing and well understood. More pictures available upon request.

Thanks!

One of the requirements by the State of Florida to apply for a concealed weapons permit is to have successfully taken a concealed carry course under a certified instructor. Miami Shooters Club provides such a course with its team of NRA certified instructors - who will teach students the important fundamentals of how to safely use a semi-automatic pistol and revolver. Your concealed weapons permit will allow you to concealed carry in more than 30 states.

Miami Shooters Club's instructors carry multiple certifications under the NRA, have traveled abroad to train and receive firearm certifications, and are hand-to-hand self defense experts - having taught multiple seminars for the Miami Dade Police Department. Under their instruction in the concealed carry class, students will learn the mechanisms behind pistols and how they operate while learning how to grip the firearm, aim, pull the trigger, get into a proper stance, and much more. The class also covers many of the legal issues and expected ethics of concealed carry in Florida. The classes are designed for complete beginners who have never touched a gun before... but experienced shooters will learn something as well.

At the end of the classroom portion, students will safely discharge a pistol under the supervision of a certified instructor, as required by the State of Florida. Miami Shooters Club will provide a firearm, ammunition, eye protection, and ear protection at no extra cost.

postcontent:
Up for sale I have a brand new, never fired AR-15 carbine rifle. The lower half is a Palmetto State Armory which has been upgraded with an A2 stock assembly. The upper half is a Tapco M4 melonited upper with 16" 1-7 twist barrel. Rifle is sold with 1 mag, as shown.

About melonite treating:

"Meloniting (nitro-carburizing) is a heat treat process for barrels that hardens the barrel to apx. 70 Rockwell so they last longer, are more corrosion resistant inside and out, and also decreases friction in the barrel which can increase velocity. Chrome lined barrels can decrease accuracy, as it is a built-up layer of material inside the barrel. Nitro-carburizing changes the structure of the metal itself without building a layer in the bore, therefore increasing performance but not decreasing accuracy. Melonite treated barrels have proven to last 30% longer than chromelined barrels, and are more accurate."

Rifle sells for $700, cash. Located in Henry County, and will only sell to individuals legal to own this firearm. Please feel free to contact for inquiries. I can be reached at REDACTED or phoned at REDACTED. If by phone, text is preferred due to complex work schedule.
